question:
Let \[f(n) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
\lfloor n \rfloor & \text{ if }n \geq 4, \\
\lceil n \rceil & \text{ if } n < 4.
\end{array}
\right.\]Find $f\left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right) + f(\sqrt{45}) + f(8^{2/3})$.

answer:
Reformatted Question: 
Let \[f(n) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
\lfloor n \rfloor & \text{ if }n \geq 4, \\
\lceil n \rceil & \text{ if } n < 4.
\end{array}
\right.\]Find $f\left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right) + f(\sqrt{45}) + f(8^{2/3})$.

Answer: 
To find $f\left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right)$, we note that $\frac{\pi}{3}$ is less than $4$, so we must use the <fact1>second</fact1> definition of $f(n)$, which gives $f\left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right) = \lceil \frac{\pi}{3} \rceil$.  Since $\frac{\pi}{3}$ is approximately $1.047$, we have $f\left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right) = 2$.  Similarly, $\sqrt{45}$ is greater than $4$, so we use the <fact2>first</fact2> definition of $f(n)$, which gives $f(\sqrt{45}) = \lfloor \sqrt{45} \rfloor$.  Since $\sqrt{45}$ is approximately $6.708$, we have $f(\sqrt{45}) = 6$.  Finally, $8^{2/3}$ is greater than $4$, so we use the <fact3>first</fact3> definition of $f(n)$, which gives $f(8^{2/3}) = \lfloor 8^{2/3} \rfloor$.  Since $8^{2/3}$ is approximately $3.174$, we have $f(8^{2/3}) = 3$.  Thus, the sum is $f\left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right) + f(\sqrt{45}) + f(8^{2/3}) = 2 + 6 + 3 = \boxed{11}$.

